initial_story: bias triangles represent features in stability diagrams of quantum dot (qd)devices, whose occurrence and property analysis are crucial indicators for spinphysics. nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and availability ofdata as well as the subtlety of physical phenomena of interest have hindered anautomatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) onhuman labelling and verification. we introduce a feature extraction frameworkfor bias triangles, built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer visionmethods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification ofphysical properties of the former. thereby, the need for human input or largetraining datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is circumvented,while additionally enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and featurelabeling. in particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (psb)detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any trainingdata as a direct result of this approach.
stories: In stability diagrams of quantum dot devices, bias triangles represent key features whose analysis is essential for understanding spin physics. However, the limited quality and availability of data, as well as the complexity of physical phenomena, have hindered the development of an automatic analysis framework. This has led to a reliance on human labelling and verification. To address this, we propose a feature extraction framework for bias triangles, based on unsupervised computer vision methods, which enables direct identification and quantification of physical properties. This approach eliminates the need for human input or large training datasets, while also automating pixel-wise shape and feature labelling. Specifically, we show that Pauli spin blockade detection can be performed effectively and efficiently without requiring any training data.

In stability diagrams of quantum dot devices, bias triangles are crucial elements that must be thoroughly analyzed to grasp spin physics fundamentals. Despite the significance of these triangles, the scarcity and poor quality of available data, combined with the intricacy of physical processes, have obstructed the creation of an automatic analysis system. As a result, human labeling and verification have become the norm. To overcome this limitation, we present a feature extraction framework for bias triangles, founded on unsupervised computer vision techniques, which enables the direct detection and quantification of physical attributes. This approach dispenses with the need for human intervention or vast training datasets, while also automating the labeling of pixel-wise shapes and features. Notably, we demonstrate that Pauli spin blockade detection can be performed accurately and efficiently without requiring any training data.

In diagrams illustrating the stability of quantum dot devices, triangular regions of bias play a vital role in understanding the fundamental principles of spin physics. Despite their importance, the scarcity and poor quality of existing data, coupled with the complexity of underlying physical processes, have hindered the development of automated analysis systems. Consequently, human labeling and verification have become the standard approach. To address this limitation, we introduce a feature extraction framework for bias triangles, grounded in unsupervised computer vision methods, enabling the direct detection and quantification of physical attributes. This approach eliminates the need for human intervention or large training datasets, while also automating the labeling of pixel-wise shapes and features. Notably, our approach can accurately and efficiently detect Pauli spin blockade without requiring any training data.
